🖥️ Slide 2 — Understanding the Product
Title:

What AfterHours Is Trying To Build

Content:

AfterHours aims to create emotionally immersive AI companionship through memory-driven conversations, evolving personalities, and long-term interaction.

Add 3 pillars:
Emotional connection
Persistent memory
Human-like interaction
Then add:

The core success metric of the app is not just engagement — but emotional retention.

🔥 This line sounds very professional.

🖥️ Slide 3 — Product Exploration Approach
Title:

How I Evaluated The App

Content:
Areas Explored
Onboarding flow
Companion interaction
Messaging experience
Group/social features
Emotional immersion
UI consistency
Add:

The analysis focused on identifying friction points that reduce emotional attachment, usability, and long-term retention.

🖥️ Slide 4 — Friction Point #1
Title:

Forced Onboarding Creates Early Friction

Add screenshot:

(Instruction/explore screen)

Content:
Observation

Users cannot skip onboarding or exploration prompts.

Impact
Slows access to core experience
Creates friction for impatient users
Reduces onboarding flexibility
Recommendation

Introduce:

“Skip”
“Quick Start”
Personalized onboarding depth
🖥️ Slide 5 — Friction Point #2 (MOST IMPORTANT)
Title:

Conversations Feel Engineered Instead of Emotionally Alive

🔥 This should be your strongest slide.

Content:
Observation

Interactions often feel system-generated rather than emotionally immersive.

Why This Matters

The app’s primary value proposition is emotional companionship.

When conversations feel predictable or artificial:

emotional trust decreases
immersion breaks
retention weakens
Product Risk

Users may perceive the app as:

a chatbot
instead of
a companion
Recommendation

Increase:

emotional unpredictability
natural pauses
region-aware conversational tone
memory callbacks with emotional depth

🔥 This slide can impress heavily.

🖥️ Slide 6 — Friction Point #3
Title:

Messaging UI Causes Interaction Errors

Add screenshot:

Small input bar / recommendation buttons

Content:
Observation

The compact message input area increases accidental taps on recommendation buttons.

Impact
Interrupts conversational flow
Reduces typing comfort
Creates frustration during longer chats
Recommendation
Larger input field
Better spacing
Reduce recommendation prominence while typing
🖥️ Slide 7 — Friction Point #4
Title:

Localization & Conversational Relatability

Content:
Observation

Frequent idioms and culturally specific phrases reduce relatability for non-native English users.

Impact
Weakens emotional realism
Creates disconnect in global markets
Recommendation

Implement:

region-aware conversational styles
simplified phrasing options
adaptive language personalization

🔥 This sounds very PM-level.

🖥️ Slide 8 — Friction Point #5
Title:

Social Features Feel Artificial

Content:
Observations
Story timestamps appear synchronized
Group chats lack tagging/mentions
Impact

These interactions feel system-generated rather than socially organic.

Recommendation
Dynamic activity timing
Message tagging system
More asynchronous social behavior
🖥️ Slide 9 — High-ROI Feature Idea (VERY IMPORTANT)
Title:

Emotion Layer Engine (Feature Proposal)

🔥 THIS is your winning feature idea.

Problem

The current interaction system feels intelligent, but not emotionally alive.

Proposed Feature

An “Emotion Layer Engine” that dynamically adjusts:

tone
pacing
vocabulary
memory references
response timing

based on:

user mood
region
conversation history
interaction frequency
Example

Instead of:

“Hope your day was fine.”

The companion could say:

“You sounded stressed yesterday. Did today get any better?”

Expected Impact
Product Benefits
Stronger emotional immersion
Increased retention
Higher daily engagement
More realistic companionship
Business Benefits
Better premium conversion
Stronger user attachment
Higher long-term usage

🔥 This is strong because it directly solves your biggest insight.

🖥️ Slide 10 — Final Conclusion
Title:

Final Thoughts

Content:

AfterHours has a strong emotional AI vision and a differentiated product direction.

The biggest opportunity lies in making interactions feel less system-generated and more emotionally authentic.

Improving emotional realism, localization, and conversational immersion can significantly strengthen long-term retention and user attachment.